Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["parsing datasets structure", "Subtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.982381229284924*^9, 
  3.9823812333422337`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7178709b-d932-42b5-a5c0-\
117eb1f915d2"],

Cell["\<\
Parsing datasets structure description:

Reference documentation stored as a plain text cell in the Mathematica \
notebook \[LongDash] this is Python code, not Mathematica. It records the \
upstream process used to access the public OpenOrganelle N5/Zarr containers \
on S3, extract a 2D intensity slice from the full 3D FIB-SEM volume, and save \
it as a CSV file. These CSVs are the input files consumed by the rest of the \
Mathematica analysis. The section is descriptive provenance, not runnable \
Mathematica.

Functions:
\[Bullet] zarr.N5FSStore() / zarr.open() \[LongDash] (Python) mounts and \
opens the remote N5 container from S3
\[Bullet] da.from_array() \[LongDash] (Python) wraps the Zarr array in a lazy \
Dask array preserving chunk structure
\[Bullet] ddata[z, y_start:y_end, x_start:x_end].compute() \[LongDash] \
(Python) extracts a 2D slice at a given z-index and computes it into a NumPy \
array
\[Bullet] np.savetxt() \[LongDash] (Python) serializes the 2D NumPy array to \
a comma-delimited CSV file

\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.987051778509858*^9, 3.9870517889249783`*^9}, {
  3.9870518286800413`*^9, 
  3.987051830149046*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e3d22b42-c847-45e3-afb9-\
9dc878e42402"],

Cell["\<\
https://github.com/janelia-cellmap/fibsem-tools#usage
https://www.openorganelle.org/datasets/jrc_hela-3
https://www.openorganelle.org/datasets/jrc_jurkat-1\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.921066069880548*^9, {3.9210694737628093`*^9, 3.921069474105522*^9}, {
   3.9853987444073057`*^9, 
   3.985398744741784*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"421063c7-fffb-4929-89b7-\
0ac8ec4ecee0"],

Cell["\<\
import fsspec, zarr
import dask.array as da
import numpy as np


# Access the root of the n5 container
group = zarr.open(zarr.N5FSStore(\[OpenCurlyQuote]s3://janelia-cosem-datasets/\
jrc_hela-3/jrc_hela-3.n5\[CloseCurlyQuote], anon=True))

# Access the full-resolution data for this particular volume
zdata = group[\[OpenCurlyQuote]em/fibsem-uint16/s0\[CloseCurlyQuote]]

# Create a Dask array from the zarr array
ddata = da.from_array(zdata, chunks=zdata.chunks)

# Define the slice you want to extract
# Note: It seems like you want a slice at a specific z-index, 5837, with \
ranges for x and y.
# However, the shape you provided earlier suggests the dimensions might be in \
a different order.
# Assuming the shape is (z, y, x), the correct slice for z=5837 would be:
slice_x_start, slice_x_end = 6290, 6700  # Adjust these values if the \
orientation is different
slice_y_start, slice_y_end = 250,500
slice_z = 5740  # Assuming this is the depth you want

# Extract the slice
result = ddata[slice_z, slice_y_start:slice_y_end, \
slice_x_start:slice_x_end].compute()

# Now, result contains the extracted slice as a numpy array

# Assuming \[OpenCurlyQuote]result\[CloseCurlyQuote] contains the 2D slice \
from the 3D dataset
# Save the 2D array to a CSV file
np.savetxt(\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]/PUTLOCATIONHERE/slice_data.csv\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote], result, delimiter=\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote],\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote])

\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.921067836469746*^9, {3.921068880085585*^9, 3.921068908059795*^9}, {
   3.921068940753504*^9, 3.921069010970539*^9}, {3.987051304917193*^9, 
   3.987051307285811*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9b0591f0-a9d1-49f6-8d4a-\
73727a03f8f3"]
}, Closed]],

